This induced gap $\Delta'_{Au}$ can be read off from the quasiparticle spectrum shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:supra_band}.
It should be noted that the whole calculation of the quasiparticle spectrum needs to be repeated with a more realistic value for $\Delta_{Nb}$,
since as we mentioned earlier for better visualization we used artificially large $\Delta_{Nb}$ in Fig.~\ref{fig:supra_band}.
While the BCS theory is valid only for the weak-coupling limit, nevertheless we apply the BCS gap equation here to the gold layers
since the induced gap is much smaller than the gap in the Nb.
To obtain the induced gap, we always take the maximum of the induced gap around the Fermi energy (as a function of $\vec{k}_{||}$)  in the Brillouin zone because the maximum of the gap is the most characteristic of the strength of the electron-phonon coupling.
In summary, the $\Delta'_{Au}$ induced gap can be read off from the calculated quasiparticle spectrum
as the function of the thickness of the gold overlayers (see Fig. \ref{fig:gap}), and the critical temperature can be calculated
from the  McMillan-formula given by Eq.~(\ref{eq:McMillan}).
Figure \ref{fig:tc} shows the critical temperature as a function of the thickness of Au overlayers obtained from the above procedure
together with experimental results taken from the papers~\cite{Yamazaki1, Yamazaki2}.
One can see clearly that our theoretical results are in very good agreement with the experimental findings, all points are within the experimental errors.
Moreover, the slow decrease of the critical temperature as function of the Au overlayer thickness is well reproduced.
We should emphasize that our theory contains only one parameter, namely the critical temperature for bulk niobium.
While in principles this quantity can be calculated~\cite{Klein}, here for simplicity we take its experimental value.

\begin{figure}[hbt!]
   \includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{./gap.jpg}
   \caption{\label{fig:gap}
            (Color online) Induced gap on the gold layers as function of the thickness of the gold.}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[hbt!]
   \includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{./tc.jpg}
   \caption{\label{fig:tc}
            (Color online) The critical temperature as function of the thickness of the gold obtained from the McMillan formula.
            The points with the error bars are the experimental results from Ref.~\cite{Yamazaki2}}
\end{figure}

Our theory presented above can be applied to other overlayer systems like NbAg, NbIr, NbAl and NbMo, and the superconducting transition temperature can be predicted.
The dependence of the critical temperature on the thickness of normal metal layers in these composites is shown in Fig.~\ref{fig:tc_more}. It can be seen that the general trend is that the superconducting transition temperature decays as the normal metal thickness is
increased for all systems, only the rate of the decay depends on the material of the overlayer.
This behavior is a consequence of the size of the induced gap in the normal
metal and also the change of the density of states at the Fermi level which enters the McMillan formula
through the effective electron-phonon coupling parameter.
This is most pronounced for the case of iridium overlayers, where the decay of transition temperature is the fastest, mostly due to the
much higher density of states at the Fermi level.

\begin{figure}[hbt!]
   \includegraphics[width=0.85\linewidth]{./more_tc.jpg}
   \caption{\label{fig:tc_more}
            (Color online) The critical temperature as function of the thickness in the case of different metal overlayers.}
\end{figure}






In summary, we have investigated the quasiparticle spectrum, and the superconducting
transition temperature of superconductor -- normal metal heterostructures.
We have developed a method to predict the transition temperature of such heterostructures based on the self-consistent solution of the
KS-BdG equations.
In the case of the niobium -- gold system we obtained very good agreement with the experimental findings.
Our theory was also applied for different metal overlayers on a Nb host to predict the superconducting transition
temperature.
Thus, our theoretical approach provides first principles based method for the systematic investigation of
superconducting thin film heterostructures.





